data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The Cosmos DB provider **never supported true synchronous I/O** — it wrapped async calls internally. The migration path was:

| Version | Behavior |
|---------|----------|
| EF Core 9 | Sync-over-async by default, opt-out warning added |
| EF Core 10 | Sync-over-async **disabled by default**, opt-in via `CosmosOptionsExtension` |
| **EF Core 11** | **Sync-over-async removed entirely** — `InvalidOperationException` at runtime |

Every call in your repository — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw because the Cosmos provider only exposes async pipelines now.

## The fix — go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key steps:**
1. Return `Task<T>` / `Task`, mark methods `async`.
2. Replace `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`.
3. `await` each call.
4. **Remove** the old sync-over-async opt-in from your `DbContextOptionsBuilder` — it's no longer recognized and will throw a config error.
5. Propagate `async/await` up through all callers (controllers, services, etc.).

> **Note:** This only affects the **Cosmos DB provider**. The relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) still support synchronous APIs natively.
